Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Identifier: Procedure for Monitoring Grants in the U.S.:
Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Explanation: Schedule I, Part I, Line 2: For those distributions labeled "donor designated pledges," no monitoring of the use of these funds is performed since the dollars are sent to the agencies at the request of the donor and, therefore, are not distributed at the discretion of United Way of Greater Milwaukee. For all the other distributions, use of the funds is closely monitored by United Way of Greater Milwaukee's (UWGM) Community Impact Division. The agencies comply with our "Agency Outcomes Policy," the impact of which is to enable UWGM to measure, in a standard fashion, the results of the programs that it funds.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Members of United Way of Greater Milwaukee's Executive Committee were provided with a copy of Form 990 prior to filing. In addition to Form 990, members of this committee were provided with an executive summary of the major items along with a listing of the key schedules for their review. The Executive Committee includes the current board chair, the prior board chair, the secretary, the treasurer, and chairs of various volunteer committees.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Part I, Line 1 AND PART III, LINE 1
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: United Way of Greater Milwaukee's Mission is to improve lives by mobilizing community resources. Last year United Way of Greater Milwaukee helped hundreds of thousands of people build and sustain better lives through opportunities in Education, Income and Health - the building blocks to a good life. United Way of Greater Milwaukee is the largest health and human services funder in the four-county area it serves: Milwaukee, Ozaukee, Washington and Waukesha Counties. It supports 160-plus programs at over 80 local agencies. Instead of focusing on one single cause or issue, United Way of Greater Milwaukee focuses on hundreds of them through strategic investments in three areas: Education, Income and Health. United Way of Greater Milwaukee services vary widely, but are each extremely important to the people who need them, whether it's to teach a child to read, help a family learn to budget and save for a home, or deliver meals to an older adult who is homebound. Pooling contributions to United Way of Greater Milwaukee empowers individuals to address a wide range of health and human service needs, making the biggest impact on their community - one person really does make a difference. And when thousands of people unite (over 71,000 donors in 2009), it allows everyone to make the greatest difference with a single charitable contribution - no matter how big or small.

Safety Net Services - United Way annually invests in a safety net of services to ensure a stable and comprehensive range of programming is available so those in our community who most need help, can find and get help. The goal is to empower people to become more self sufficient and independent over time. The service priority areas are: *Basic needs - More than a quarter of the people in metropolitan Milwaukee live in poverty without enough money to provide adequate food, housing and health care. United Way connects them to the urgent help they need. *Self-sufficiency - United Way funds programs that help achieve independence. Self-sufficiency focuses on programs like youth development, older adult independence and programs for people with disabilities. *Strengthening families and children - United Way promotes healthy family relationships through programs like counseling, day care, and domestic violence prevention and relief because a community is only as strong and successful as its families.

Research shows that the best way to help the most people is to get to the heart of problems in order to prevent them from happening in the first place. About one in four people lives in poverty, and one-third of all children suffer from poverty. United Way's strategy for breaking the cycle of poverty is to focus on the underlying causes that keep people from gaining income and becoming economically independent. The goal is to create lasting change and decrease the community's long term needs. The focus areas are: *Early childhood education - United Way invests in early childhood education because research indicates that a child's third grade reading level directly influences whether he or she graduates from high school. Children involved in quality early childhood education programs are more likely to succeed in school and in their adult lives, increasing the likelihood of attending college or a trade program and earning higher wages. *Reducing teen pregnancy and sexual violence against girls - Two thirds of teen moms never graduate from high school; teen moms are less apt to get a job paying above minimum wage and 75% rely on public assistance. Up to two-thirds were sexually assaulted prior to their first pregnancy. United Way is focused on preventing teen pregnancy because it perpetuates poverty. In April 2008, United Way of Greater Milwaukee-led communitywide Teen Pregnancy Prevention Initiative announced an aggressive goal to reduce births to teens by 46% by 2015. At the time, the rate of births to 15- to 17-year-old girls was 55.4 (or 55.4 births per 1,000). In just three years, United Way has successfully reduced Milwaukee's teen birth rate to its lowest rate in over 30 years - 2010 represented the third consecutive drop to 44.41, which continues to buck national upward trends in births to teens. *Job training and retention - By investing in job skill training and technical trades, United Way supports a more competent workforce, empowering individuals to qualify for employment leading to income while concurrently meeting the needs of the business community. In particular program, 78% of participants in a United Way job-readiness program completed the program and secured sustainable employment. *Asset building - United Way, along with the federal government and private sector organizations, matches up to $6 for every dollar saved by qualifying individuals for purchase of a home or post-secondary education. United Way assists low-income individuals in obtaining a higher education or become a home owner because both are pathways out poverty and into financial stability. Children of home owners are more likely to do well in school, less likely to have behavioral problems or become pregnant as teens. United Way's program has helped 153 families purchase homes, equaling an $10.2 million mortgage investment in the community.

Strategies & Goals United Way of Greater Milwaukee's Philosophy: Everyone deserves opportunities to build a good life - a quality education that leads to a stable job, enough income to support a family through all of life's stages, good health and a safe home. United Way of Greater Milwaukee's Goal: To create long-lasting change by addressing our community's most serious problems through providing access to high-quality basic needs services and breaking the cycle of poverty. United Way of Greater Milwaukee's Strategy: Focus on three critical issue areas - Education, Income and Health - the building blocks to a good life. Education - Helping Children and Youth Achieve Their Potential Today's young Americans are less likely to earn diplomas than their parents, a distinction not shared by any other industrialized country. United Way of Greater Milwaukee is changing that reality by boosting every child's chance for success in school, work and life. Objectives: Increase the number of children who *Enter school ready to succeed. *Read proficiently by 4th grade. *Graduate from high school on time. *Are prepared for success in college, work and life. Income - Promoting Financial Stability and Independence As many as one-third of working Americans do not earn enough money to meet their basic needs and have no ability to save for college, a home, or retirement. United Way of Greater Milwaukee provides tools that help families increase and maximize their income to meet daily expenses, and begin the longer-term process of saving and building assets. Objectives: Increase the number of adults and families who *Earn enough income to meet daily expenses and basic needs. *Have skills to gain and sustain employment. *Save for and build assets like home ownership or postsecondary education. Health - Providing Basic Needs and Improving People's Health and Safety Health impacts every aspect of a person's daily life. United Way of Greater Milwaukee ensures people have access to basic human needs like food and shelter, and resources to live healthy lives from prenatal programs to end-of-life care, and everything in between. Objectives: Increase access to *Emergency resources and basic needs like food and shelter. *Physical and mental health care, dental care and affordable prescriptions. *Substance abuse, child abuse and family violence prevention services. *A support network to help individuals with cognitive and physical disabilities live independently, and with dignity. *Resources to help older adults remain healthy and safe in their own homes. Accountability United Way of Greater Milwaukee is trustworthy and effective. It only invests in programs that produce results at agencies that manage their money wisely. Plus, United Way of Greater Milwaukee operates at a high rate of efficiency with 90 cents of every dollar raised invested into community problem solving. This far exceeds the 65-percent-minimum considered acceptable for a nonprofit to be living up to its mission. Donors trust United Way of Greater Milwaukee because 100 percent of the programs United Way of Greater Milwaukee invests in must demonstrate program effectiveness and financial accountability and provide data on the demographics of the people United Way of Greater Milwaukee-funded services are helping. United Way of Greater Milwaukee measures results by the individual lives changed and the overall impact on Greater Milwaukee. Some examples of measurable effectiveness by issue are below. Education *Until 3rd grade, children are learning to read. After 4th grade, they're reading to learn. By 4th grade, a child's grades and absenteeism can predict with 90% accuracy whether he or she will graduate from high school on time. *United Way result: 91% of children in United Way youth programs say they try harder to do their best in school. Income *Research indicates that as little as 10 hours of personal financial education positively affects spending and savings habits. Our nation's personal savings rate in 2006 was -1%, the lowest in 73 years. Over 40% of the average U.S. family's net worth is in the form of home equity. *United Way result: the average Milwaukee homeowner was seven times more likely to foreclose compared to individuals who attended United Way home pre-purchase classes. Health *Milwaukee has one of the highest teen birth rates in the country. *United Way result: In October 2010, the City of Milwaukee Health Department announced Milwaukee's teen birth rate declined for the third year in a row thanks to United Way's leadership in addressing the issue and convening communitywide organizations to combine efforts.
